content:
Can you provide two opposing statements to the following quote using JavaScript code:
"A wise parson once said, “money is an opportunity to do good.”"
[JavaScript code]: 
const quote = "A wise parson once said, “money is an opportunity to do good.”";
const opposite1 = "Money is a source of evil and corruption.";
const opposite2 = "Money is a means to satisfy personal greed and selfishness.";
console.log(opposite1);
console.log(opposite2);

Certainly! Here's a JavaScript code snippet that provides two opposing statements to the given quote:

```javascript
const quote = "A wise parson once said, “money is an opportunity to do good.”";
const opposite1 = "Money is a source of evil and corruption.";
const opposite2 = "Money is a means to satisfy personal greed and selfishness.";
console.log(opposite1);
console.log(opposite2);
```

This code defines the original quote and two opposing statements, then logs the opposing statements to the console.
